origin: Late Middle English (meaning ‘doer’, also in the Scots sense ‘agent’): from French facteur or Latin factor, from fact- ‘done’, from the verb facere.

definitions.definition: A circumstance, fact, or influence that contributes to a result or outcome.
definitions.example: she worked fast, conscious of the time factor

definitions.definition: A number or quantity that when multiplied with another produces a given number or expression.
definitions.example: an amount that exceeds it by a factor of 1000 or more

definitions.definition: Any of a number of substances in the blood, mostly identified by numerals, which are involved in coagulation.
definitions.example: These include a change in the balance between procoagulant and anticoagulant factors in the blood.

definitions.definition: A business agent; a merchant buying and selling on commission.
definitions.example: his father was chief factor for the Hudson's Bay Company
last year researchers factored a number 155 digits long

definitions.definition: Organize (the source code of a piece of software) into different components that are easier to maintain and work with.
Sell (one's receivable debts) to a factor.
definitions.example: they collected rents while he factored these forfeited estates
